          "body": "The chapter's theological center is 7:13-14, and it pivots on the single imperative 'consider' — look carefully at the work of God. The question that follows is rhetorical and devastating: 'Who is able to straighten what He has bent?' No one. The image of divine bending (avat) is not cruel but sovereign: God shapes the contours of events, and human wisdom cannot reconfigure what He has decreed. The immediate application is to the alternation of prosperity and adversity in 7:14. Both days come from God's hand; both require a prescribed response — happiness in the good day, careful consideration in the bad. But the deeper purpose is stated in the chapter's most important purpose clause: God has made the one as well as the other 'so that man will not discover anything that will be after him' (7:14). The inscrutability of the future is not a flaw in Providence but its design. God deliberately prevents the kind of foreknowledge that would allow man to live independently of trust. This is the chapter's theological backbone; every proverb before it and every imperative after it is calibrated to this reality. Trevin Wax and Keller both note that Ecclesiastes functions as a kind of pre-evangelistic apologetic, dismantling the pretense of autonomous human competence before the one who reads it will hear the gospel of grace."
