          "title": "The limits of wisdom — Qohelet's autobiographical confession",
          "body": "The chapter closes with one of the most candid autobiographical passages in the Old Testament (7:23-29). Qohelet set himself to be wise — not merely to study wisdom but to possess it as his own achievement — and found it stood far from him (7:23). The mystery is not merely intellectual depth but existential inaccessibility: what has been is 'remote and exceedingly mysterious' (7:24). He turned his heart to investigate the full spectrum of human experience, including the evil of folly and the foolishness of madness (7:25). What he found in the course of that investigation was a particular kind of danger — more bitter than death — in the person whose heart is 'snares and nets' and whose hands are 'chains' (7:26). The figure is not a generic warning against women but, in the Proverbs tradition, a personification of seductive folly — the 'Strange Woman' of Proverbs 2:16-19, 5:3-5, 7:6-27 — who lures the undiscerning away from wisdom and life. The God-pleaser escapes; the sinner is captured. The final confession (7:28-29) is painful: Qohelet found one upright man in a thousand but no upright woman — a statement that many commentators, including Longman and Eaton, read as reflecting the corrupt social environment of his investigation rather than a universal ontological claim about women. What he found with certainty is the one thing the chapter ends with: God made man upright, and man has multiplied schemes. The fall is the deep grammar of the whole chapter's disorder. Qohelet's investigation ends where the biblical narrative begins: human corruption is not God's fault but man's own contrivance."
